, started to overlap and became globally understood and used by ever larger groups of people. These themes are brought to life by a diverse set of key primary sources, such as a book, a letter, a medal, a temple and an epic, to showcase how historians have used sources to tell these stories and conduct debates. The book provides an introductory resource into the study of history and includes detailed suggestions for further study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aDiachronic. 4aGeneral and world history. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aHistory: specific events and topics. 4aHistory: theory and methods. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aHistory of Communication, Silk Roads, Political Order, Slavery and Race, History and Religion, War, Identity, Modernity, Human Rights, Ecology.1 aBoogert, Jochem van den, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDa Via, Elisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuyvesteyn, Isabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuyvesteyn, Isabelle, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGriffiths, Richard T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLing, Gina van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNae, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRee, Arnout van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScarborough, Isaac, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmidli, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShaev,